Sort Product Prices for End-of-Day Reporting

A retail analytics team in Chennai receives an unsorted list of product prices recorded throughout the day. Before generating the end-of-day report, the prices must be arranged in ascending order so that trends, minimum values, maximum values, and comparisons become easier.

Given an integer array, sort the array in ascending order and print the sorted result.

Input format :
The first line contains an integer n — the size of the array
The second line contains n space-separated integers
Output format :
First line: print the sorted array in ascending order
  
Code constraints :
1 <= n <= 5 * 10^4
-5 * 10^4 <= nums[i] <= 5 * 10^4
  
Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
4
5 2 3 1
Output 1 :
1 2 3 5
Input 2 :
5
5 1 1 2 0
Output 2 :
0 1 1 2 5


solution:


// You are using Java
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main(){
    
    int n;
    cin>>n;
    
    vector<int>arr(n);
    
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        cin>>arr[i];
    
    for(int i=0;i<n-1;i++){
        
        for(int j=i+1;j<n;j++){
            if(arr[i] > arr[j]){
                swap(arr[i],arr[j]);
            }
        }
    }
    
    for(int i:arr){
        cout<<i<<" ";
    }
}
